# Git Conventions

## Commits
- Conventional Commits format: `type(scope): imperative summary`
  - `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `style`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `build`, `ci`
  - Example: `fix(search): abort stale requests before rendering suggestions`
- Summary ≤ 72 chars, imperative mood ("add", not "added"/"adds"). Body explains WHY when the diff alone can't.
- One logical change per commit. Never mix a feature with an unrelated refactor or formatting sweep.
- Never commit: secrets, `.env`, build artifacts, `node_modules`, `.DS_Store`, editor junk, commented-out code, `console.log` debugging leftovers.

## Workflow
- Never commit or push unless I explicitly ask.
- Before committing: run `git status` and `git diff --staged` — stage deliberately (specific paths), review what's actually going in. No blind `git add -A` when unrelated files are dirty.
- Work on branches for anything non-trivial: `feat/…`, `fix/…`, `chore/…`. Don't commit straight to `main` unless the repo is single-player and I say so.
- Destructive operations (`push --force`, `reset --hard`, `checkout .`, `clean`, history rewrites, deleting branches) — NEVER without my explicit confirmation for that specific command. Prefer `--force-with-lease` if force-push is approved.
- Don't amend or rebase commits that are already pushed/shared.

## Pull Requests
- Title follows the same conventional format as commits.
- Description: what changed, why, how it was tested, screenshots for UI changes, and any follow-ups deliberately left out.
- Keep PRs reviewable: one concern, roughly ≤ 400 changed lines where possible; split otherwise.
